WRITING.TEXT: My group of 10 and I were returning to the U.S. from Honduras today after a week-long work-and-witness trip to build a church. Our flight landed in Houston 30 minutes EARLY and we had no trouble having our passports checked and turning in the form that lists the souvenirs we brought back. Even our baggage claim experience was quick and painless. But then we entered a line that literally snaked around the entire baggage claim area. We had an hour and a half layover before catching our flight to Wichita, but standing in that line took all 90 minutes and we hadn't yet gone through security. The long line was for one of two border security agents to look at the traveler, look at their passport, then wave them through. Didn't check carry-on or checked bags, didn't ask us to declare anything, didn't even speak to us. Just a seemingly mindless exercise that made us (and thousands others, it was obvious) miss our flight. It was just one big bottleneck where a few thousand people spent 30 seconds each, and it delayed everyone. Other airport staff actually climbed onto one of the baggage carousels to take photos of the long lines. It was ridiculous. Of course, this was the last flight to Wichita, so we missed the flight and now our group had to spend hundreds of dollars on hotel rooms and dinner in Houston. United Airlines wouldn't help us because it's not their fault the lines at the airport were wrong. Can the airport or TSA or border security be held responsible for making us miss our connecting flight even though we arrived 30 minutes ahead of airline schedule?

Fake? Come on. Why would I take the time to make this up? Yes, we used the kiosks, which was a smooth process. That's where you electronically claim anything aside from luggage that you're bringing into the U.S. That process scanned my passport and took a photo of me and also required an agent to manually check my passport. We thought we were in the clear after moving swiftly through that area. But then after we got our luggage we ran into the long line that bottlenecked everyone into two agents redundantly checking passports. Made no sense. Update: Red Roof Inn was HOPPING last night with people who missed their flights because of the delays. Overnight we got what I think are the remnants of Hurricane Patricia here in Houston so there are more delays this morning. We'll get home eventually; it's just frustrating because it seems a more common sense, efficient system would have allowed us to avoid all this.

We have a 1.5-year-old female akita, and she's great. Intelligent and stubborn, at times, but the patience necessary to raise her has been worth it. We expected her to be larger (her father was 120 pounds), but she seems to be maxing out at 75 points. That's plenty big enough for us. Here in Kansas it drops to 0 Fahrenheit in the winter and gets up to 100 Fahrenheit in the summer. She likes the winter more than the summer, but she's fine in either, though we keep her primarily indoors. When we got her as a 10-week-old puppy we introduced her to our 6-year-old male Westie. Both are fixed, which probably helps, but they get along perfectly well. My wife, a therapist, user our akita as a therapy dog. She hasn't passed the training yet to be an official therapy dog, so she's still just a "therapy dog in training" but my wife's clients love having our akita in the office during therapy sessions. I'd highly recommend some type of interactive training class for you and your akita. You'll need just as much training as your akita does. Hope this helps!

Yes, our akita has been significantly more difficult to train than our westie. I'd say they're equally intelligent, but if the akita doesn't want to sit, she won't sit. She fully understands the sit command; sometimes she's just not interested in sitting. So she won't. Stubborn. My wife has had a hard time getting the akita to follow more advanced commands required to pass the therapy dog test, like sitting still while other dogs play near her or allowing children to touch her tail or head without trying to lick them. But she's only a year and a half old and we are making progress. But the important things like house training and leash walking were equally easy. Just start early and be consistent. My wife and I read about negative experiences with akitas, but we haven't experienced the aggression or destruction that others have, fortunately.
